Page 3: Filesystem Types & Storage Hardware
Filesystem Types:
Windows: NTFS, FAT32, exFAT
.
Linux: ext4, ext3
.
MAC: APFS
.
File Operations:
Create, Read, Write, Append, Delete, Open, Close
.
Storage Types:
HDD (Hard Disk Drive):
Mechanical (spinning disk)
.
Slower and cheaper
.
Components: Has a platter (spinning disk) and a Read/Write head
.
Process: Head moves to the correct track (Seek Time) → Disk rotates → Data is read
.
SSD (Solid-State Drive):
No moving parts
.
Faster but more expensive
.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Page 4: SSD Performance
How SSD Works:
SSDs use Flash memory
.
They provide direct access to memory cells, leading to faster performance
.
Disk Access Time Formula: Seek Time+Rotational Delay+Transfer Time
.
Because SSDs use direct access rather than mechanical movement, they are significantly faster than HDDs
.
